<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05011l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05011l">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05011l"> 11(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> menstruating ape</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Gerald Massey, referring to &ldquo;the moon of the menses as well as the mensis; writes:. &ldquo;This mystical moon was related to the <mark>menstruating ape</mark>; hence, as Hor-Apollo says, the cynocephali were brought up in the Egyptian temples in order that the priests might ascertain the exact instant of the conjunction of the sun and moon. Women were devoted to the same purpose, and made use of as demonstrators by the monthly Prognosticators and others who are denounced as servants of the excrementitious gods in the Hebrew Scriptures.&rdquo; <small> G.W. Foote, <a name="BROM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BROM"><cite title="source">Bible Romances</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1922) [The Creation Story] 18n</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
